[2
Date: 11 Oct 2000
From: M. Cosgriff <mcosgriff@hotmail.com>
Source: Electronic Telegraph, 11 Oct 2000 [edited

BSE-infected meat 'could still be in human food chain' - UK
------------------------------------------------------
Meat infected with BSE could still be finding its way into the human food
supply because of a legal loophole, the chairman of the Food Standards
Agency (FSA) warned yesterday.
Sir John Krebs promised a tightening of the regulations after warning
farmers could be allowing meat having not been inspected for the disease
to reach the open market. Beef from animals killed on a farm or in an
unlicensed abattoir for the owner or relatives to eat was exempt from
the rules introduced to keep BSE out of the human food chain.
Cattle aged over 30 months were also deemed unfit for human consumption but
the rule did not apply to meat from a private kill, he said. Sir John
called for stronger safeguards to ensure such meat was not being made
available for public consumption, particularly in rural areas. There was no
way of ensuring parts such as brains and spinal tissues - feared to be the
most dangerous part of an infected animal - had been properly removed, he
said. "That's precisely why we're concerned about both the extent to which
this goes on and the possibility meat or meat products from private kills
might get into the wider food chain.
"We want to make sure in the longer term work is done to tighten up this
loophole." The FSA said there was not enough information available to
assess the scale of the problem, and advised consumers in rural areas to
make sure any meat they bought was "from a reputable source".
Peter Scott, director of the British Meat Federation, which represents
abattoirs, called for the end of the exemptions for privately killed
animals. He said: "This is a problem for the FSA and it's a dilemma which
they, and before them the Ministry of Agriculture, have faced for a number
of years. But our view hasn't changed. We
believe, in this day and age, if there's any risk at all, then that
loophole must be closed."
