[3
Date: 11 Oct 2000
From: M. Cosgriff <mcosgriff@hotmail.com>
Source: Reuters, 11 Oct 2000 [edited
US Has Low Risk of Mad Cow Disease
----------------------------------
An aggressive U.S. government program to monitor cattle health means the
risk of BSE occurring in this nation is "extremely low," a U.S. science
research group said in a new report.
The brain-wasting disease has been found in Great Britain and 9 other
European countries, but no cases have ever been found in the United States.
A report issued on Monday by the Council for Agricultural Science and
Technology summarized the latest information and disease statistics on BSE
and other transmissible spongiform encephalopathies (TSEs), a group of
neurological diseases that can be fatal for humans and other animals.
The council, based in Ames, Iowa, is composed of 38 scientific societies
interpreting scientific research and provide advice for lawmakers and
federal regulators. The report described the U.S. risk of BSE as
"extremely low."
Other TSE diseases have occurred in the US, including Creutzfeldt-Jakob
disease (CJD) in humans, scrapie in sheep and goats, chronic wasting
disease in deer and elk, and transmissible mink encephalopathy.
In July a flock of Vermont sheep originating in Belgium was suspected of
carrying TSE. Farmers and the U.S. Department of Agriculture (USDA) have
been battling over whether the sheep should be destroyed, or returned to
Belgium.
U.S. officials launched a surveillance program in 1990 to detect and
prevent the introduction of BSE. The program is run by several government
agencies and more than 250 federal and state regulatory veterinarians are
trained to diagnose the disease.
To fight scrapie, the U.S. government and industry have a surveillance
program tracing exposed animals back to the farm of origin. The USDA
recently proposed new rules for scrapie control by restricting interstate
movement of sheep and goats and establishing
pilot projects to evaluate flock cleanup plans based on testing.
The U.S. government also has a surveillance program for chronic wasting
disease, which is found in free-ranging deer and elk in 10 counties of
north-central Colorado and southeastern Wyoming. Transmissible mink
encephalopathy is a rare disease, with only 5 U.S. outbreaks recorded, the
last in 1985.
A copy of the 36-page report is available on the Internet at
<http://www.cast-science.org.>
